    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and trace.csv. For metric.csv: group by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute for each group: count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), and the global P95 of value. Return at most top 20 rows sorted by count desc. Also list the distinct cmdb_id values and the distinct kpi_name values (with counts). For trace.csv: group by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute for each group: count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), and the global P95 of value. Return at most top 20 rows sorted by count desc. Finally, report the overall min and max timestamp across both files. Keep outputs compact and bounded."}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step loaded metric.csv and trace.csv and computed per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) and per-(cmdb_id,trace_name) summaries including counts and global P95s. Observations from those results: the metric data covers 2020-05-30 03:00:00+08 through 2020-05-30 04:00:00+08. Many node and db KPIs have 61 samples (full hour) while many docker/container trace metrics only start at 03:30 and have 30 samples (03:30–03:59), which matches the incident window (03:30–04:00). Trace groups show docker_001 has many trace features in the 03:30–03:59 window (high p95 values for some durations). Given the single failure occurred between 03:30 and 04:00, we should now detect metric anomalies within that incident window relative to global thresholds computed on the entire available series (not just the incident window). To find candidate faulty components, we must identify component-KPI points inside 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 to 2020-05-30 04:00:00+08 that breach their global thresholds. We'll detect both high-side breaches (value >= global P95) and low-side breaches (value <= global P5) because some KPIs (e.g., success rate) indicate failure when they drop. From those breaches we will produce compact aggregates: anomaly count in window, earliest anomaly timestamp, and maximum breach severity for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window for threshold calculation). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window: timestamps between 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 and 2020-05-30 04:00:00+08 inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name), detect anomaly points in the window where value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5. Aggregate these anomalies per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) to produce: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (as datetime in Asia/Shanghai), and max_breach_severity (for high breaches use max((value - P95)/P95), for low breaches use max((P5 - value)/P5); report the larger magnitude if both types occur). Return at most top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc. Also return a single-line summary count of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) that had anomalies. Keep outputs compact." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full metric series and then filtered metric points to the incident window (2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 to 04:00:00+08). We flagged anomaly points in the window where value >= global_P95 or value <= global_P5 and aggregated them per (cmdb_id,kpi_name). The result shows a very large candidate set: 1993 distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) had anomalies in the window. Top metric candidates include many os_* disk and IO KPIs, multiple db_* KPIs, and various other counters. Because the number of metric anomalies is large, we need to narrow candidates using trace data (per the workflow: metric analysis -> trace analysis -> log analysis). Traces can help identify the most downstream faulty container/service in call chains and reduce the candidate set to container/service-level components active in the incident window (03:30–04:00). Next, we should perform the same thresholding logic on trace features (compute global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id,trace_name) using full trace series, then detect anomalies in the incident window) and aggregate by component to find which containers/services have the most severe or earliest trace anomalies. This will give a compact list of trace-level suspect components to focus further fault-identification (consecutive-fault detection) and then correlate with metric KPIs for root cause reason determination.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full available series (do NOT filter by the incident window for threshold calculation). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window: timestamps between 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 and 2020-05-30 04:00:00+08 inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name), detect anomaly points in the window where value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5. Aggregate anomalies per cmdb_id to produce: total_anomaly_count (sum across trace_names), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai), and max_breach_severity (compute severity similarly as for metrics: for high breaches (value - P95)/P95, for low breaches (P5 - value)/P5; use the larger magnitude if both types occur). Return at most top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by total_anomaly_count desc. Also return the distinct count of cmdb_id that had any trace anomalies in the window. Keep outputs compact and bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated trace anomalies across the incident window and found container-level components (docker_001..docker_004 etc.) dominate anomaly counts. docker_001 had the highest total_anomaly_count and a large max_breach_severity (≈1.96), indicating severe deviations in trace features during 03:30–04:00. Multiple containers show anomalies starting at 03:30:00+08 (the beginning of the incident window). To localize the root cause component and reason, we must inspect which specific trace features on the top container candidates are anomalous (for example: jdbc.*, remoteprocess.*, self.*duration_p95/mean, error_rate). Traces that show abnormal JDBC durations/error_rate or remoteprocess durations can indicate downstream DB issues or network delays/loss. Therefore the next step is to extract per-trace_name anomaly details for the top container candidates (docker_001, docker_002, docker_003, docker_004) including anomaly counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, and max breach severity for each trace_name so we can determine whether DB-related traces (jdbc/remoteprocess) or network-related traces (remoteprocess latency, error_rate) are the most severe.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to the incident window 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 through 2020-05-30 04:00:00+08. Using the global thresholds previously computed per (cmdb_id, trace_name) (do NOT recompute thresholds from incident-only data), detect anomaly points where value >= global_P95 or value <= global_P5. For the following cmdb_id list: ['docker_001','docker_002','docker_003','docker_004'], aggregate anomalies per (cmdb_id, trace_name) to produce these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai), max_breach_severity (use the same severity definition as before). Return up to top 100 rows but limit display to the top 20 rows sorted by cmdb_id then anomaly_count desc. Also return one-line counts: number of distinct trace_name anomalies per each of these cmdb_id. Keep outputs compact and bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected trace anomalies in the incident window and found container-level traces dominate. docker_001 stands out: it has the highest total trace anomaly count and large breach severity on trace.self.jdbc.duration_p95 (max_breach_severity ≈ 1.96) with anomalies starting at 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08. Many trace error_rate and remoteprocess.* metrics for docker_001 are also anomalous (error_rate flagged but with NaN severity likely due to zero-based thresholds). This pattern (large JDBC p95 spikes on docker_001) suggests a downstream database latency or connectivity issue affecting JDBC calls from docker_001 starting at the beginning of the incident window. To confirm whether the root cause is in the DB (connection limit/close) or network (delay/loss) or node-level CPU, we must inspect DB-side metrics for db_* components within the same window. Specifically, we should aggregate metric anomalies for all db_* components in the window (03:30–04:00+08) using the previously computed global thresholds and report anomaly counts, earliest anomaly times, max breach severities, and the top contributing KPI names per DB. This will tell us whether DB(s) show concurrent severe anomalies (e.g., tnsping_result_time, Row_Lock, Hang, connection-related KPIs) that align with docker_001's JDBC spike.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric anomalies already computed with global thresholds, filter anomaly records to the incident window 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 through 2020-05-30 04:00:00+08. From those anomaly records, select rows whose cmdb_id begins with 'db_' (all db_* components). For each db_* cmdb_id, produce: cmdb_id, total_anomaly_count (sum of anomalies across KPIs), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai), max_breach_severity (largest magnitude breach among its KPIs), and the top 5 KPI names by anomaly_count for that db (with their counts). Return up to top 20 db rows sorted by total_anomaly_count descending. Also return a single-line count of distinct db_* components that had any anomalies in the window. Keep outputs compact and bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "We performed metric- and trace-level anomaly detection using global thresholds computed on the full series, then filtered to the incident window (2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 to 04:00:00+08). Results so far: trace analysis shows docker_001 (and other docker_* containers) had many trace anomalies starting at 03:30, and docker_001 exhibits a pronounced spike in trace.self.jdbc.duration_p95 (max_breach_severity ≈ 1.96) with earliest anomaly at 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 — this indicates client-side JDBC latency observed in the container. Metric analysis across db_* components shows many DBs (db_001..db_013) with severe anomalies in the same window; several DBs have extremely large breach severities (e.g., db_010 severity ≈ 835, db_011 reported inf, db_002 severity ≈82), and many DB KPIs related to tnsping_result_time, Hang, ACS, AIOS, Row_Lock, Login_Peak, etc. All DB anomalies begin at 03:30. According to the diagnosis rules, when faults appear at different levels and one level shows much larger deviation (>>50%), that level is likely the root cause level — here DB-level deviations are far larger than container-level trace deviations, so the root cause level is likely the DB(s). However, multiple db_* services show faults; to localize the single root cause component (single failure) we must identify which DB is the most downstream faulty service in the call chain from the affected container(s) or which DB shows the earliest and most severe DB-specific KPI fault that can explain the JDBC p95 spike on docker_001. Therefore we need per-KPI anomaly detail for the top DB candidates (those with the largest breach severity) to determine which DB had the primary failure and the exact occurrence time and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the metric anomaly records already computed (global thresholds on full series, anomalies filtered to 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08..04:00:00+08), select anomalies for db_* components. Identify the top 5 db_* components sorted by their max_breach_severity (descending). For each of these top 5 db_* components, aggregate anomalies per kpi_name to produce: db cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai), and max_breach_severity (for that KPI). Return up to 50 rows but display only the top 20 rows sorted by cmdb_id then anomaly_count desc. Also return a single line listing the top 5 db cmdb_ids selected (in order). Keep output compact." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed preprocess -> anomaly detection -> metric & trace analysis. Metrics show many db_* components with severe anomalies starting at 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08; trace analysis shows docker_001 experienced a strong JDBC p95 spike at 03:30:00+08, indicating client-observed DB latency. Among DBs, db_011 and db_010 had the largest breach severities (db_011 reported 'inf', db_010 ≈835), and the top-5 DBs by severity were db_011, db_010, db_002, db_009, db_006. Per the localization rules, the root-cause level is likely DB (service) because DB KPIs deviate far more than container-level traces. To pick the single root-cause DB and exact occurrence time and reason, we must inspect the DB-side KPI details (which KPI first crossed thresholds, their actual values in the incident window, and global thresholds). This will tell us whether the DB experienced a hang/IO stall/connection-timeout (db close/connection limit) or network issues. The next step is to fetch, for db_011, the global thresholds (P95 and P5) for its top KPIs (e.g., Hang, tnsping_result_time, ACS, AIOS, AWS) computed on the full metric series, and to list db_011's metric datapoints for those KPIs inside the incident window 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08..04:00:00+08 (timestamp, kpi_name, value), sorted by timestamp. This will confirm the exact first anomalous timestamp and the dominant symptom (e.g., Hang or tnsping spikes).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For cmdb_id = 'db_011': 1) Using the full metric.csv series (do NOT filter before threshold calc), compute global P95 and P5 for every kpi_name belonging to db_011. 2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window 2020-05-30 03:30:00+08 through 2020-05-30 04:00:00+08 inclusive and select rows for db_011 whose kpi_name is one of the top KPIs observed earlier (at least: Hang, tnsping_result_time, ACS, AIOS, AWS). 3) Return a compact table showing for each selected kpi_name: global_P95, global_P5, and then the metric rows in the incident window with columns (timestamp as datetime Asia/Shanghai, kpi_name, value), sorted by timestamp ascending. Limit metric rows returned to at most 50. Also return a one-line earliest anomalous timestamp for db_011 (the first timestamp in the window where value >= P95 or <= P5 for any of these KPIs). Keep outputs compact and bounded."
}

